		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> A month later...<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.62)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10224'>Lucas "skitch" Heath</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10224&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> December 3, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Well it&#39;s a month in to open format and some have already decided that raiders are TTs Sauron, and that Dunland is a flop... well for what its worth here are my thoughts on the strengths / weaknesses of the game a month after the two towers release.<br />
<br />
This article is very long and should probably be read in parts, so I&#39;ll split it up into 3 parts for you to read at your own discretion.<br />
<br />
I&#39;ll go culture by culture:<br />
<br />
Dunland:<br />
Dunland is not as weak as some make it out to be, but without Hides it certainly is.  It is not smart of Decipher to make the culture so dependent on one card, especially a rare card that newer players won&#39;t be able to collect multiples of.  The only other card half as powerful in Dunland is No Retreat, but it&#39;s nowhere near a necessity, plus you only need one or two.<br />
I guess you could say Moria was like this with Armories, but my comment would be that Moria is at least playable without Armories... I don&#39;t think Dunland is without Hides.  How fun would it be to you if every time you played a minion, you knew it and one or two more wouldn&#39;t make it into the skirmish phase?<br />
The thing I like about Dunland is that it brings a new element into the game... They give you an easy way of doing things that are strengths of other cultures.  Possession discarding in particular is a powerful part of the Nazgul strategy, but is so much more simple with Dunland.  War Clubs and especially Wild Man Raid provide simple ways of discarding tonnes of possessions, without a lot of hassle, and it&#39;s much harder to stop.  Cantea is easily made less powerful when assigned to say Gandalf w/ Shadowfax and Staff or a Horned in Elrond, etc, Wild Man Raid cannot be stopped, and many times will be the hand that opens the gate for some big guys with War Clubs to discard a couple more weapons.<br />
The other aspect Dunland brings is its ability to take control out of the Free Peoples hands.  Possession removal does this in the sense that it nullifies the ability of a fellowship to win skirmishes, and sometimes will makes the difference for a &quot;take control of a site minion&quot; who leads to the use of No Retreat.  No Retreat takes away the free peoples player control completely, and many times will give you an easy win.  Although hard to get into play and use effectively it is the most powerful thing Dunland has, and one of the most powerful cards in the game.<br />
Keep in mind though that without Hides, none of these cards are effective enough to make Dunland worth playing.<br />
<br />
Dwarves:<br />
Dwarves have always appealed to those who were in search of good fun... they have never been very powerful, and it&#39;s doubtful that they&#39;ve won more than 1 or 2 big tournaments in your area.  I do think the new idea behind the culture, I think it&#39;s pretty cool, but the fact that you have to discard a card on your own most times keeps me from playing it.  With the introduction of Eomer & Faramir into the card game, I don&#39;t know if Gimli is even worth playing in most decks.  The Gimli and Legolas deck is probably the best possibility, but even that is not tournament worthy for the single fact that Grima would absolutely kill it.  <br />
The best thing about dwarves is that you know some off-the-wall player in your area will build a really cool deck out of it, that actually beats you and reminds you that anything can happen in this crazy game.<br />
<br />
Elves:<br />
Elven Allies have ruled since Fellowship, so the culture has faded as a superpower with the new focus on companions, because the main purpose of the new Elven cards is to create the All-elven fellowship.  Legolas, Dauntless Hunter is easily the best card in the culture, but we can look at him as a support companion for other cultures, even the common legolas does not fit in with his counterparts.  Blades Drawn when played right could be one of the best cards in the game, the only set-back is spotting 3 elves to play it... making it Elves-only.  Card drawing is still a big bonus of this culture with Alliance Reforged and Lembas making Elves a great fellowship side to a Shadow-kill deck like Moria or even Dunland.<br />
The Naiths are really not that good being that they are built for strength in battle, but really aren&#39;t very strong, the best new companion has got to be Lorien Swordsman, although very weak in strength, this guy can beat a Cave Troll under the right circumstances.  I almost hope for a new Arwen that has this guys ability or another Haldir, I think a unique companion with this text is needed.  The best option I see right now for those who want to play ALL elves is the Blades Drawn deck, with Men like Faramir and Aragorn who carry bows and can use Last Alliances... card drawing is still a must as these decks get big fast!  Elves prove that you can have fun and win at the same time, and I don&#39;t doubt an Elf deck or two will walk away with a tournament in your area.<br />
<br />
Gandalf:<br />
The Gandalf Culture neither gets better nor worse with the onset of TT strategies.  He remains what he always has been.  The most versatile support companion in most decks, and the most powerful fighter in Gandalf based (i.e. Trust) decks.  The biggest additions are of course Treebeard and Shadowfax and both have their own significant effect.  Sure the rare Treebeard is practically a requirement in an unbound hobbit deck, but don&#39;t forget he&#39;s a site 8 ally... having help at site 8 is almost too much especially considering how little help site 8 gives the shadow player (unless he&#39;s playing Dunland).  I also think people overlook the ability of common Treebeard... sure his ability isn&#39;t great, but he reduces hand clog in decks like Trust Me, where say Aragorn doesn&#39;t take too many wounds.  Shadowfax is great because it adds strength without being a hand weapon which many cards key off, like Cantea and Golden Hall.  It also prevents Easterling exertions and even a guy like Wulf from taking a site.  With his staff, Gandalf is a potential Damage +4, so no more worries about Uruk Vanguard fierce skirmishes, just make sure you win the first time (not a hard thing to do with Gandalf).  The last important card here is Hearken to Me know which is the most obvious link between Rohan and Gandalf.  This link is much more broad than that, both cultures work very well together, and it is my belief that the synergy between Gandalf and Aragorn will spill into Rohan, making mount decks a powerful multicultural strategy.<br />
<br />
Gondor:<br />
What can I say about the rangers?  Everyone seems to use them, even though they have a huge flaw: no condition removal (athelas is pretty limited).  That said Gondor has distanced itself from the rest as the super power of the fellowship.  The new gondor rangers are the most balanced, most powerful, and most solid of all the cultures and are the most likely to succeed as a one culture deck.  Although some say they are broken they do have many draw-backs.  One of these is the lack of condition removal I mentioned, they are also very susceptible to possession removal, and lastly that they are easy to counter.<br />
Nazgul and Dunland in particular hurt not because of their low site numbers but because of their different strengths: Nazgul w/ Black Breaths and Tips kill Rangers because Rangers must exert quite a bit, and most people don&#39;t throw brands into their Ranger decks.  Dunland hurts because of possession removal and because you have very little archery.  Granted you could be playing a different type of Ranger deck than I have seen, but for the most part these two cultures do the most damage.<br />
The last counter that I can think of is any type of wounding deck, because those are usually pretty powerful against little condition removal.  Sauron comes to mind, but you might as well use Uruk Archery...  beats everything anyways.  Oh yeah, and Moria is good against ANYONE who doesn&#39;t have condition removal.<br />
That said, Rangers spank Uruks around if you use Defend it and Hope and Mablung pretty much stops anything big from doing damage.  The domain cards can make a difference, but in a culture packed with so many good cards it just isn&#39;t worth it.  That actually seems to be a huge problem with Gondor now, is that it has too many good cards, and quite a few great cards.  How can you build a Gondor deck without Faramir&#39;s Cloak, Ranger Bows and Swords of Gondor?  You&#39;ll also want Armor, Ithilien Trap, Defend it and Hope, Arrows Thick in the Air and a couple boosters... after that you go back to Fellowship stuff and you want Shards, Citadel, maybe Athelas, maybe Gondor Bowman, probably No Strangers...  You usually end up with a 38-42 card deck that you have to a cut a bunch out of...<br />
The last thing I want to say about Gondor is that it has what is surely going to be the most overlooked power card in the set.  Ithilien Trap is the answer to Grima, Enquea, basically anything that exerts to really hurt you.  And the cost is practically nothing.  It costs 2, and you add tokens when you win skirmishes, which you tend to do with men...<br />
<br />
Thanks for reading part One, and thank you for your reviews.  Join me for part 2 where I cover Isengard, Moria and Nazgul. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=4230&view=1&PHPSESSID=0313aa87643b71a0b7ad3aab95c5ef45'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=0313aa87643b71a0b7ad3aab95c5ef45'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=0313aa87643b71a0b7ad3aab95c5ef45'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
